The augur therefore directed his attention solely to a part of the heavens in which an omen would be favour- able, and did not at all observe the unluclty side. Those who take advantage of the superstitious feelings of others generally know very well how to suit their dicta to the wishes and likings of the credulous. Such was certainly the system in the later ages of Rome, but it may be doubted whether it was really in practice so early as the time of Numa, when in all probability the augurs them— selves believed in the truth of their art, and the observation of the heavens was consequently more than a mere form.
